                    <!-- Myth 1 -->
                    <div role="listitem" class="w-dyn-item">
                        <div class="service-item">
                            <div class="service-item-left">
                                <div class="service-number">03</div>
                                <a href="#" class="service-title">“Climate change is just natural variability.”</a>
                                <div class="service-info">
                                    <p class="service-summary">
                                        Natural cycles exist—but cannot explain the observed rate or magnitude of modern
                                        warming. Physics-based attribution studies show the current energy imbalance
                                        aligns with greenhouse gas forcing, not orbital or solar changes.
                                    </p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Myth 2 -->
                    <div role="listitem" class="w-dyn-item">
                        <div class="service-item">
                            <div class="service-item-left">
                                <div class="service-number">04</div>
                                <a href="#" class="service-title">“CO₂ is a trace gas—too small to matter.”</a>
                                <div class="service-info">
                                    <p class="service-summary">
                                        CO₂’s radiative importance depends on infrared absorption, not concentration
                                        alone. Even trace gases can dominate radiative forcing when they absorb in
                                        otherwise transparent atmospheric windows.
                                    </p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Myth 3 -->
                    <div role="listitem" class="w-dyn-item">
                        <div class="service-item">
                            <div class="service-item-left">
                                <div class="service-number">05</div>
                                <a href="#" class="service-title">“Models can’t be trusted—they’re always wrong.”</a>
                                <div class="service-info">
                                    <p class="service-summary">
                                        Models are testable physical frameworks. While imperfect, they reproduce
                                        large-scale energy balance and trends verified by satellite and surface
                                        observations. Their uncertainties are quantifiable, not disqualifying.
                                    </p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Myth 4 -->
                    <div role="listitem" class="w-dyn-item">
                        <div class="service-item">
                            <div class="service-item-left">
                                <div class="service-number">06</div>
                                <a href="#" class="service-title">“Scientists disagree on global warming.”</a>
                                <div class="service-info">
                                    <p class="service-summary">
                                        Multiple independent studies find over 97 % of climate scientists agree that
                                        human activity is warming the planet. Apparent “debate” often arises from
                                        misrepresentation or non-expert amplification.
                                    </p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Myth 5 -->
                    <div role="listitem" class="w-dyn-item">
                        <div class="service-item">
                            <div class="service-item-left">
                                <div class="service-number">07</div>
                                <a href="#" class="service-title">“The climate has changed before—so this is normal.”</a>
                                <div class="service-info">
                                    <p class="service-summary">
                                        Past climate changes were driven by orbital, volcanic, and solar variations
                                        acting over millennia. Today’s rapid shift—occurring within decades—matches the
                                        fingerprint of anthropogenic greenhouse forcing.
                                    </p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Myth 6 -->
                    <div role="listitem" class="w-dyn-item">
                        <div class="service-item">
                            <div class="service-item-left">
                                <div class="service-number">08</div>
                                <a href="#" class="service-title">“It’s cold outside—so global warming must be fake.”</a>
                                <div class="service-info">
                                    <p class="service-summary">
                                        Weather and climate operate on different scales. Local cold events do not negate
                                        global trends; in fact, a warmer atmosphere can amplify extreme patterns by
                                        altering jet-stream dynamics and moisture availability.
                                    </p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>
